        <item>
			<title>Verse 10 of 14 on Meditation: Nirvana is non-attainment</title>
            <link><![CDATA[http://deerpark.libsyn.com/verse-10-of-14-on-meditation-nirvana-is-non-attainment]]></link>
            <description><![CDATA[<p>Dear Friends</p>
<p>We are so happy and thankful to Thay Phap Hai for this beautiful teaching. &nbsp;The readings are also a wonderful reminder how much all of us non-monastics owe Anathapindika. &nbsp;He is the one who, on his deathbed, shared with the sangha that us laypeople could understand the deep teachings of the dharma. &nbsp;Let us live in such a way as to be worthy of his confidence.</p>
<p><strong>Verse 10:</strong></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Nirvana is non-attainment</p>
<p>Sudden or gradual enlightenment are not different.</p>
<p>True realization is to live in freedom</p>
<p>right now in this moment.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Reflection Questions:</p>
<p>1) Do I notice times when I feel the need to be right? How does this manifest in&nbsp;thought, word and action?</p>
<p>2) What situations do I notice more of a push to be right, or to prove my point?&nbsp;How does this feel in my body? In my mind?</p>
<p>3) If I can sit with that experience, am I able to discover anything underneath?</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Readings: &nbsp;Discourse on Teachings to be Given to the Sick</p>]]></description>
            <guid isPermaLink="false"><![CDATA[7d0c1c0b77b5219d264b08a167e1b167]]></guid>
